From: compact-sb-db <compact-sb-db@local>
Date: Thu, 19 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] safe_browsing: support zstd-compressed compact store files

Teaches V4Store to load .zst-compressed database files produced by
sb_compact.py.  The compressed file contains a standard V4StoreFileFormat
protobuf with 3-byte hash prefixes; no changes to the lookup or update
paths are needed because HashPrefixMap already handles any prefix size.

Changes
-------
  components/safe_browsing/core/browser/db/v4_store.cc   — ReadFromDisk
  components/safe_browsing/core/browser/db/v4_store.h    — declaration
  components/safe_browsing/core/browser/db/BUILD.gn      — zstd dep

How it works
------------
  ReadFromDisk() checks whether the file begins with the 4-byte zstd
  frame magic (0x28 0xB5 0x2F 0xFD).  If so it decompresses the entire
  file into a buffer and passes that buffer to the existing protobuf
  parsing path.  Everything downstream is unchanged.

  WriteToDisk() is intentionally NOT modified.  Chromium continues to
  write uncompressed files when it fetches a new update from Google.
  The compact .zst file is a read-only deployment artifact produced
  offline by sb_compact.py; Chromium never re-writes it.

  When Chromium fetches an update from the Safe Browsing API it will
  write a new uncompressed .store.4_XXXX file as usual.  After that
  point the compact file is no longer used.  Re-run sb_compact.py on
  the new file if you want to go back to the compact format.

False-positive note
-------------------
  3-byte prefixes produce ~24% false positives per URL lookup
  (vs ~0.10% for 4-byte).  Chromium resolves false positives by sending
  a full-hash request to the Safe Browsing API, so network access must
  remain available.

