Notes on applying this patch
─────────────────────────────

1.  Locate the Chromium source checkout and apply:

      cd $CHROMIUM_SRC
      git apply v4_store_compact.patch

    If the patch context lines don't match your exact revision, apply
    manually — the changes are small and clearly delimited.

2.  The zstd library is already vendored in Chromium at:

      third_party/zstd/

    The BUILD.gn change simply adds it as a dep of safe_browsing_db.
    No new source downloads required.

3.  Rebuild the target:

      autoninja -C out/Default chrome
      # or for Android:
      autoninja -C out/Default chrome_public_apk

4.  File placement
    ──────────────
    Copy the two output files from sb_compact.py into Chromium's
    Safe Browsing database directory:

      Linux/Mac:  ~/.config/chromium/Default/Safe Browsing/
      Windows:    %LOCALAPPDATA%\Chromium\User Data\Default\Safe Browsing\

    Files to copy:
      UrlSoceng.store.compact        (metadata, ~92 bytes)
      UrlSoceng.store.compact.zst    (compressed hash DB, ~9.6 MB)

    The standard UrlSoceng.store and UrlSoceng.store.4_XXXX files can
    be left in place or removed; Chromium prefers the file listed in
    the .store metadata file.

    IMPORTANT: update UrlSoceng.store.compact to reference the .zst
    filename as the data file (sb_compact.py does this automatically).

5.  Update trigger
    ──────────────
    When Chromium fetches a Safe Browsing update from Google it writes
    a new UrlSoceng.store.4_NEWID file and updates UrlSoceng.store to
    point to it.  At that point the compact file is no longer used.
    Re-run sb_compact.py on the new file to restore the compact format.

6.  Reverting
    ─────────
    To revert to the standard format, remove the .compact files and
    ensure the original UrlSoceng.store points to a valid .4_XXXX file.
    No revert of the C++ patch is necessary — uncompressed files pass
    through MaybeDecompress() unchanged.
